TI  - Game-theoretic analysis of recycling integration modes in a power battery supply chain under carbon trading and deposit-return mechanisms
AU  - Liu, Bin
AU  - Liu, Hao
AU  - Gao, Anqi
T2  - JOURNAL OF CLEANER PRODUCTION
AB  - This study aims to identify the optimal recycling integration modes in a power battery supply chain-comprising a battery manufacturer, an EV manufacturer, and a third-party recycler-under a carbon trading mechanism. Four distinct modes are proposed: the non-integration mode(NA), the integration mode between battery manufacturers and third-party recyclers (PT), the integration mode between battery manufacturers and automobile manufacturers (PM), and a fully integrated mode that involves all three parties (AL). Game theory is employed to analyze the pricing decisions of supply chain stakeholders across each mode. Results reveal increased recycling competition intensity leads to lower supply chain profits in all modes except Mode AL. Mode PM achieves the highest overall supply chain profit at lower competition intensity, while Mode AL becomes more profitable under high competition intensity. From the perspective of individual participants, Mode PM is more beneficial for battery and automobile manufacturers at low competition intensity. In contrast, Mode AL fosters a win-win situation for all parties under high competition intensity. Additionally, rising carbon trading prices result in higher battery prices across all modes, with Mode AL achieving the highest battery recycling rate in scenarios of intense competition. This suggests that Mode PM and Mode AL are optimal for low and high-competition intensity environments, offering strategic guidance for integration mode selection and designing more sustainable, coordinated battery supply chains under evolving market and policy pressures.
